  "prompt": "How do I know if a shy guy likes me?",
  "response": "Determining whether a shy guy likes you can be a bit tricky, as shyness might make him less likely to express his feelings openly. However, there are several signs you can look for:\n\n1. **Body Language**: Pay attention to his body language when he's around you. If he leans in when you talk, maintains eye contact, or mirrors your gestures, these can be signs of interest.\n\n2. **Nervousness**: A shy guy might show signs of nervousness around you, such as fidgeting, stumbling over words, or blushing.\n\n3. **Engagement**: Notice how often he engages in conversation with you. If he seeks out opportunities to talk, even if it's brief, it could indicate that he likes you.\n\n4. **Listening Intently**: If he remembers details from your conversations or asks follow-up questions, it shows that he values what you say and is interested in you.\n\n5. **Compliments**: Pay attention to any compliments he may give you, even if they are subtle. Shy individuals might compliment you in a less overt way.\n\n6. **Social Media Interaction**: If he's active on social media, look for signs that he interacts with you more than others, such as liking your posts or leaving comments.\n\n7. **Finding Excuses to Be Around You**: If he often finds reasons to be near you or to hang out in group settings, it could be a sign he likes you.\n\n8. **Supportive Behavior**: If he goes out of his way to help you or support you in various situations, it shows he cares.\n\n9. **Playful Teasing**: Sometimes, playful teasing can be a sign of affection, so if he jokes with you in a friendly manner, it might mean he has feelings for you.\n\n10. **Group Dynamics**: Observe how he behaves when you\u2019re in a group. Does he seem particularly attentive to you or act differently from when he\u2019s with others?\n\nIf you notice several of these signs, it's possible that he has feelings for you. If you're comfortable, you could also consider initiating a casual conversation to see how he responds and gauge his interest further. Sometimes, taking the first step can help ease his shyness!",
